social_posts.post_text:
“Marionette, No. 1”

Bringing #TheCoolPeople into the physical realm, stage one. This is just a little taste — more brewing. 

Hand built with wood & fully painted in an old world style, this marionette displays beautifully on the wall with hooks as a sculpture & doubles as a simple working mechanism with a pull chain at the top + a handle bar operating the arms. Organic motion follows.

Created November 2022. Will be on display at @gallery23ny @ 807 Washington St, NYC this coming week.
synchronicities are spinning today 🔮 🧠

social_posts.post_text:
This work of art was stolen last night at the gallery event between 7:30-8pm. The piece was already sold to a client. If you know who was involved or have video footage from that time period, please contact me. We had door security, so this is quite baffling. 

The universe works in mysterious ways. Karma will take the lead. There is nothing cool about stealing. The painting was created with respect for nature’s flow and divine beauty. Hopefully The Driftwood Relic’s energy will provide healing with whoever she’s floating around with now. 

I’m accepting this as a compliment to my artistry. Bad Fortune enlightens, always. Luckily, my unbelievably cool client shares my positive mojo and will choose another piece from the collection to replace the loss. Nobody will harsh our mellow. ✨

Absolutely honored to be featured in @amnewyork at @gallery23ny with the legends @sarit_peretz1002 and @dadiperetz ❤️‍🔥 The team at G23NY are insanely hardworking and driven to grow the @meatpackingny arts community. Could not be luckier to work with them. Also mad grateful for @strangemajik and his presence in my arts career. Whole heartedly jazzed for future collaborations, collections, & projects! The world is our oyster! 🌎 🔥

Thank you @bobkrasner @bobkrasnertoo for shooting and writing this amazing little moment in time. 🙏

Storm Ritter just keeps moving forward. A painter first and foremost, she is also an entrepreneur who sells a line of hand-painted clothes, a designer of textiles and the creator of her own line of jewelry.

Although she had a shop for a number of years on 8th Street near the Electric Ladyland studio, she has no immediate plans for another retail outlet.

“I never do the same thing twice,” she explains. At present she is ensconced in a “pop up” at Gallery 23 on Washington Street in the Meatpacking District — a situation that was supposed to go for two weeks in September but continues on through at least this month, with the possibility of staying on through March up in the air.

Now 30, Ritter celebrated that milestone birthday recently with a bash at the gallery featuring live music by local talent Strange Majik. Her artistic journey began in Dunedin, FL, where her “hippie rock-and-roller parents instilled a wonderful work ethic” in their daughter.

One of the things that sets Ritter apart from the crowd is a mind for business. Even before she studied that subject at NYU, she managed to sell the giant man-eating props that she created as a junior for a high school production of “Little Shop of Horrors” to a commercial theatre company.

After high school, she jumped around a bit, studying a variety of subjects (in and out of school) such as set design, philosophy, fine art, enlightenment theory, art history and vintage pop culture while struggling to overcome dyslexia and working various day jobs while attending school at night and eventually graduating with honors from NYU Gallatin.

I had the privilege recently to visit my elementary and middle school to deliver a memorial plaque and a small piece of artwork to honor our art teacher, Mrs. Weezie Kempf. Beyond touched to speak in front of the entire student body of 400 cool kids, amazing teachers & the lovely Kempf family ❤️‍🔥

Mrs. Kempf was an iconic art teacher in all my years of education. She taught art in primary school, but moreover Weezie gave me the gift of confidence and inner power in myself, which is a very hard thing to teach. When I heard the news of Mrs. Kempf’s passing, I knew I wanted to show appreciation for what she influenced in my life. Mrs. Kempf made a huge difference in how I soulfully interact with the world. She invited me to feel like I am an artist and could grow into a stronger artist of life. Her positive energy rubbed off on me. She would always speak about “happy accidents” – that there are no mistakes in art, just opportunities to flow. Turn a problem into a solution! The quote is a metaphor for life. When problems arise, you need to put a positive twist on things. Every accident is an opportunity to learn. I have had many phenomenal teachers, and it’s the little things that stick with you. 

I wanted to make sure her memory and positive energy would continue to inspire students like she did for me. Recently at one of my events at @gallery23ny — I organized a silent auction of a few of my pieces to raise funds for the plaque and monetary donation for a new yearly award in her name for a passionate 8th grade student. Thank you everyone who contributed to this effort. 

Directly inspired from Mrs. Kempf, don’t let anyone harsh your mellow. Whatever you want to be or do, work consistently and do it! If you get a NO, turn it into a YES. If there’s an accident, make it happy. 🙂 Thank you @espiritusantoschool 🥰

"Where Do The Children Play"
41.5 x 53 inches 
Latex, leather paint, oil on wood
Oil, leather paint on wood frame (Refurbished)
2023 NYC

🤍 This piece was specifically made for donation to the @yourpartfoundation “Humanitarian Aid Art Auction for Ukraine” 🇺🇦 at 821 Washington Street, Meatpacking NYC @gallery23ny on Thursday, May 4th, 2023, 6-9pm. 

🔮 When I paint, I typically listen to one song on repeat, infusing the music into the colors and composition. This song “Where Do The Children Play” by #CatStevens is a beautiful theme for this concept and soulful story. The wood was primed and painted with color palette in mind, completed with satin varnish. The frame was stripped, primed and painted with oil and leather paint. 

🌎 The profits raised in the art auction will directly go towards funding for medical supplies for doctors in Ukraine, directly benefiting children in need. 

⭐️ About @yourpartfoundation 
"All auction proceeds go to the purchase of medical supplies and equipment for doctors operating in Ukraine's war-torn cities. Since February 2022: millions have been displaced from their homes, close to 20,000 civilians have been murdered, and countless have been injured. Doctors and medical staff working in Ukraine are conducting surgeries under constant bombardment and limited supplies. Your Part Foundation stands on the side of peace for those victims of senseless war and oppression."
